{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_0","type":"agent_message","text":"**Topology Summary**\n\nUse a first-order passive RC high-pass filter. Drive `Vin` with an explicit independent AC source referenced to node `0`. Place `C1` in series from `Vin` to `Vout`, and place `R1` from `Vout` to `0`. The output `Vout` is the capacitor/resistor junction. This gives DC blocking and passes higher-frequency content to the load resistor.\n\n**Device/Function List**\n\n- `V1`: independent AC source from `Vin` to `0`, AC magnitude `1`\n- `C1 = 1uF`: series coupling element between `Vin` and `Vout`\n- `R1 = 1k`: shunt/output return element from `Vout` to `0`\n\n**Bias/Reference Strategy**\n\nNo supply rails are needed. Node `0` is the only reference. DC operating point is naturally defined because `R1` gives `Vout` a return to ground; `Vin` is explicitly driven by `V1`. No extra bias network is required for AC analysis.\n\n**Signal Or Feedback Path**\n\nSignal path is `V1 -> Vin -> C1 -> Vout`, with `R1` returning `Vout` to `0`. There is no active feedback path; this is a purely passive single-pole network. At low frequency, capacitor reactance is large so `Vout` is attenuated. At high frequency, capacitor reactance falls and `Vout` approaches `Vin`.\n\n**SPICE/Netlist Constraints**\n\n- Preserve node names exactly: `Vin`, `Vout`\n- Keep `V1` explicit from `Vin` to `0`\n- Connect `C1` only between `Vin` and `Vout`\n- Connect `R1` only between `Vout` and `0`\n- Use only primitive SPICE elements\n- Include `.ac dec 20 1 1e9`\n- Expected cutoff is about `1 / (2*pi*1k*1uF) ~= 159 Hz`\n\n**Failure Risks To Avoid**\n\n- Do not swap the RC order; `R1` must be the shunt element at `Vout`, not a series input resistor\n- Do not connect `Vout` on the source side of `C1`\n- Do not omit `R1`, or `Vout` will float\n- Do not rename or alias `Vin`/`Vout`\n- Do not replace the RC network with behavioral or controlled-source equivalents\n- Do not leave the input implicit; `Vin` must be directly driven by `V1`"}}
